Today, mother died. Or maybe yesterday, I don't know. I received a telegram from the home: "Mother deceased. Funeral tomorrow. Sincerely yours." That doesn't mean anything. It may have been yesterday. 

The heat was already intense by the time I started walking toward the beach. The sun was a weight on my shoulders, pressing down through the dry air. The sea was calm, almost motionless, reflecting the white glare of the sky like a sheet of polished metal. I walked along the shoreline, the sand hot beneath my feet. There was no sound except for the dry crunch of shells under my steps and the distant, rhythmic sigh of the waves.

I met Raymond near the rocks. He was angry about something, but his anger seemed distant to me, like something happening behind a pane of glass. He asked me if I wanted to walk further down the coast. I said it didn't matter, but that we could if he wanted to. 

The sun was getting hotter, the light reflecting off the water in sharp, blinding flashes. I could feel the sweat gathering in my eyebrows and running down my temples. The glare was unbearable, almost hostile. It was the same sun that had shone on the day of the funeral, the same heavy heat that made the asphalt soft under our shoes.

I walked toward the cool shadow of the rock. An Arab was lying there, watching us. He didn't move, but the light caught the blade of his knife as he drew it. The steel flashed in my eyes, a single spark of burning light. The heat was pushing against me, the sea was breathing fire, and the sky seemed to split open to rain down sheets of flame. 

I took a step forward. I didn't think about it. I squeezed my hand on the metal of the revolver. The trigger gave way. The sound was deafening, a sharp crack that shattered the silence of the beach. The Arab fell. I stood there for a moment in the blinding light. Then, I fired four more times into the motionless body. It was like knocking four quick times on the door of unhappiness.
